<ns6062:section xmlns:ns6062="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.ooLanguage.compositionVersusAssociation.compilationUnits">
    
    <ns6063:title xmlns:ns6063="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Compilation Units</ns6063:title>

<ns6064:para xmlns:ns6064="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Traditionally a compilation unit is a file -- in the case of java it is the
Java source/ file (<ns6065:emphasis xmlns:ns6065="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="verb">Name.java</ns6065:emphasis>). The source/ code need not, however, be
located in a file. Some Java development environments store the source/ code
directly in a repositry which makes team development a lot easier.</ns6064:para>

<ns6066:para xmlns:ns6066="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Nevertheless, Java enforces one rule on compilation units. There may be only
one public class or interface per compilation unit. This typically makes the
individual compilation units small and enhances reusibility.</ns6066:para>
    
</ns6062:section>